{{Infobox Bilateral relations|China-Iceland|China|Iceland}}
[[File:Chinese embassy in Reykjavík.jpg|thumb|The Chinese embassy in Reykjavík]]
'''China – Iceland relations''' are foreign relations between [[China]] and [[Iceland]]. Diplomatic relations between them were established on December 8, 1971.  China has an embassy in [[Reykjavík]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Foreign missions|url=http://www.mfa.is/diplomatic-missions/foreign-missions|publisher=Icelandic Ministry of Foreign Affairs|accessdate=24 May 2015}}</ref> Iceland has an embassy in [[Beijing]] and an honorary counsulate in [[Hong Kong]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Icelandic missions|url=http://www.mfa.is/diplomatic-missions/icelandic-missions|publisher=Icelandic Ministry of Foreign Affairs|accessdate=24 May 2015}}</ref>

== History == 
In May 1972, China assigned the first resident ambassador to Iceland. In 1995, Iceland set up its embassy in Beijing and assigned its first resident ambassador to China. In December 1995, China resumed the practice of sending resident ambassadors to Iceland (between 1983 and 1995, the Chinese ambassador to [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]], was also accredited to Iceland).

In 2010, Enex, an Icelandic firm, signed an agreement on digging for geothermal energy in [[Inner Mongolia]] and [[Shaanxi]], China.<ref>{{cite web|title=Iceland banks on geothermal for economic expansion|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2010/oct/12/iceland-banks-geothermal-economic|website=The Guardian|accessdate=7 July 2015}}</ref>

In 2011, Chinese tycoon Huang Nubo offered to buy [[Grímsstaðir]] in North-East Iceland. The deal fell through.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hands off our wilderness|url=http://www.economist.com/node/21530165|website=The economist|accessdate=7 July 2015}}</ref>

In 2013, Iceland signed a free trade agreement with China. This was the first Chinese free trade agreement with a European country.<ref>{{cite web|title=Iceland Is First in Europe to Sign Free Trade Pact With China|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-04-15/iceland-is-first-in-europe-to-sign-free-trade-pact-with-china|website=Bloomberg|accessdate=7 July 2015}}</ref>

